            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Days Until calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool counts the number of days between two calendar dates.
                By default it uses today as the start date, but you can change
                both the start and end dates, include or exclude today, and
                optionally count only business days (Monday to Friday).
              </p>

              <h3>Basic formula for days between dates</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  <strong>Raw days difference (exclusive)</strong><br />
                  \( \text{days} = \dfrac{\text{endDate} -
                  \text{startDate}}{86\,400\,000} \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm mt-2">
                  where 86,400,000 is the number of milliseconds in one day.
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mt-3">
                  <strong>If you include today</strong><br />
                  \( \text{daysIncludingToday} = \text{days} + 1 \) (when end
                  date ≥ start date)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                The calculator normalizes both dates to midnight in your local
                time zone to avoid off‑by‑one errors caused by time of day or
                daylight saving changes.
              </p>

              <h3>Counting business days only</h3>
              <p>
                When you enable <strong>Business days only</strong>, the
                calculator loops from the start date to the end date and counts
                only days that fall on Monday–Friday. Weekends (Saturday and
                Sunday) are excluded. Public holidays are not excluded
                automatically.
              </p>

              <h3>Understanding the outputs</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Days</strong> – the main result, adjusted for your
                  Include today choice.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Weeks</strong> – days divided by 7.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Months (approx.)</strong> – days divided by 30.44
                  (average days per month).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Years (approx.)</strong> – days divided by 365.25
                  (accounts for leap years on average).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Business days</strong> – Monday–Friday between the two
                  dates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weekend days</strong> – Saturdays and Sundays between
                  the two dates.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Examples</h2>
              <h3>Example 1 – Days until New Year</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose today is <strong>October 1, 2025</strong> and you want
                to know how many days are left until
                <strong>January 1, 2026</strong>.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Set start date = 2025‑10‑01.</li>
                <li>Set end date = 2026‑01‑01.</li>
                <li>Leave <em>Include today</em> unchecked.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator will show the exact number of days between those
                dates, plus the equivalent in weeks, months, and years.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Business days until a deadline</h3>
              <p>
                You start a project on <strong>March 4</strong> and the deadline
                is <strong>March 29</strong>. You want to know how many working
                days you have.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Start date = March 4.</li>
                <li>End date = March 29.</li>
                <li>Turn on <em>Business days only</em>.</li>
                <li>
                  Choose whether to include today depending on when you start
                  working.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator will show the total calendar days, business days,
                and weekend days between those dates.
              </p>

